President Cyril Ramaphosa addresses the nation at Waterkloof Airforce base on the first coronavirus case in South Africa. Courtesy #DStv403 PRETORIA - President Cyril Ramaphosa has called on South Africans to stay calm following the confirmation of the country's first coronavirus case. A 38-year-old man has tested positive for the (COVID-19) virus in KwaZulu-Natal. The man recently travelled to Italy and has been in self-isolation since. READ: Health system will be tested by coronavirus: Mkhize Ramaphosa says South Africa is prepared to deal with Covid-19. “So we are gearing up more as a country and the report I have received from the minister of health has demonstrated to me that we can be more art and go to higher levels of being alert. WATCH: MPs debate coronavirus outbreak Meanwhile, Health Minister Dr Zweli Mkhize says a tracer team has been dispatched in KwaZulu-Natal. The minister said epidemiologists, clinicians from the National Institute for Communicable Diseases are also in KZN. Mkhize said the Emergency Operations Centre will be running 24-hours from now on.